        {
            "id": "e50b438b6e8f40ddb5f5a",
            "questionText": "A bat emits a sonar pulse at a frequency of $!$40 \\text{ kHz}$!$ to detect a moth flying directly away from it. The bat is flying at a speed of $!$10 \\text{ m/s}$!$, and the moth is flying at a speed of $!$5 \\text{ m/s}$!$, both relative to the air. Given that the speed of sound in air is $!$343 \\text{ m/s}$!$, determine the frequency of the echo as perceived by the bat in $!$\\text{kHz}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "9f50e0fc47a54aeca6e3f",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the appropriate Doppler effect formula for the first leg of the problem where the bat is a moving source and the moth is a moving observer. Choose the formula that relates the original frequency $!$f$!$ to the frequency received by the observer based on the speeds of the source and observer.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a20069a8-ca33-4e26-93ce-87c105e52c27",
                        "73f17e12-18ff-4466-adf7-e5551d71bc83",
                        "a738c7c2-d0ca-4760-8351-7ce0f93d7404"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f' = f \\left(\\frac{v - u_{observer}}{v - u_{source}}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f' = f \\left(\\frac{v + u_{observer}}{v - u_{source}}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f' = f \\left(\\frac{v - u_{observer}}{v + u_{source}}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "9fc574ba336440ae85c2a",
                    "stepText": "Now, substitute the given values $!$v=343\\,m/s$!$, $!$u_{source}=10\\,m/s$!$, $!$u_{observer}=5\\,m/s$!$, and $!$f=40\\,kHz$!$ into the formula you selected in Step 1. Calculate the intermediate frequency received by the moth.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "40.6"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kHz",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a20069a8-ca33-4e26-93ce-87c105e52c27",
                        "8004f091-3866-4725-923f-566d362ee31a",
                        "bbf4917b-1be4-4827-b1ae-ddfdaa7124a9"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "d21595f60b954d41a86e9",
                    "stepText": "Great, now consider the return journey where the moth acts as a moving reflector (or source) and the bat becomes the moving observer. Identify the correct Doppler effect formula for this scenario. Which one correctly represents the relationship between the frequency emitted by the reflector and the frequency detected by the bat?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
